  "doi": "10.1016/j.celrep.2024.114555",
  "title": "Public T cell clonotypes are selected in HLA-B\u221757:01+/HIV+ patients independently of the viral load.",
  "journal": "Cell reports",
  "year": 2024,
  "authors": "Chatzileontiadou DSM, Lobos CA, Robson H, Almedia CA, Szeto C, Castley A, D'Orsogna LJ, Gras S."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study examines TW10-specific T cell responses in HLA-B\u221757:01\u2013positive HIV+ patients, focusing on the Gag-derived epitope TW10 presented by the protective HLA-B\u221757:01 allele. The researchers identified a striking public TCR clonotype and strong TRBV5 bias in the TW10-specific TCR repertoire, and solved the crystal structure of the HLA-B\u221757:01\u2013TW10\u2013TCR complex to reveal the structural basis for this biased recognition. Despite low TCR affinity, TW10-specific T cells mounted polyfunctional responses independently of viral load, suggesting that TCR-pMHC geometry and public clonotype selection\u2014rather than affinity or antigen abundance\u2014drive protective T cell control in HIV controllers. This work provides mechanistic insight into why a particular HLA allele and epitope are enriched in HIV controllers and has implications for understanding TCR repertoire constraints in infection-driven T cell selection and vaccine design targeting conserved viral epitopes.",
